cial consciousness provided an axis for social solidarity as well as partial insulation from racial slights, and how the suburb afforded these middle-class residents a degree of physical and social distance from the ghetto. As Haynes explores the history of Runyon Heights, we learn the ways in which its black middle class dealt with the tensions between the political interests of race and the material interests of class.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zYonkersxEconomic conditions. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zYonkersxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zYonkersxSocial conditions. 0aEthnic neighborhoodszNew York (State)zYonkersxHistory. 0aMiddle classzNew York (State)zYonkersxHistory. 0aSocial classeszNew York (State)zYonkersxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300129861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300129861.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO